A Go-based Temporal Workflow manages a long-running cluster provisioning job. It spawns multiple Child Workflows using `PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON` and also accumulates substantial event history over days of operation. The team adds Update handlers to accept real-time configuration changes. A senior engineer proposes this Continue-As-New guard:

```go
func (cm *ClusterManager) shouldContinueAsNew(ctx workflow.Context) bool {
    return workflow.GetInfo(ctx).GetContinueAsNewSuggested() ||
        (cm.maxHistoryLength > 0 &&
         workflow.GetInfo(ctx).GetCurrentHistoryLength() > cm.maxHistoryLength)
}

// In the main workflow loop:
if cm.shouldContinueAsNew(ctx) {
    return ClusterManagerResult{}, workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(
        ctx, ClusterManagerWorkflow, ClusterManagerInput{State: &cm.state})
}
```

The Workflow is also receiving frequent Update requests during peak hours. In production, engineers observe that some Updates appear to complete successfully from the client's perspective, but the state changes they requested are silently dropped after a Continue-As-New boundary. What is the most likely root cause?
